Create the Calendar table and connect it to the FactTable. 2

 

Step 2.1 - Create the Calendar Table.

1. In Power Bi, go to the Data view.





2. Click on New table from the Calculation menu inside the Table Tools tab.

3. Type in the formula bar the <Calendar = Calendarauto(12)>. This will generate the Date column.

4. Click on the Date column.

5. Go to Format located in the Formatting menu in the Column Tools tab. Change the format of the Date column to “03/14/2001 (mm/dd/yyyy)”.

  


 



Step 2.2 - Create a relationship between tables.

1. In the Data model, drag the date field from the FactTable to the Date field in the Calendar table. This will create a relationship.

2. Go to Manage relationships in the Relationships menu located in the Home tab.

3. This is the only relationship so far. Double click on it to open the Edit relationship menu.

4. Select the many to one option in the Cardinality and the Single option in the Cross-filter direction. Click OK, then close in the Manage Relationship window.

5. You should see the relationship flowing from the Calendar table to the Fact table.






Step 2.3 - Mark the calendar table as the Date Table.

1. Select the Calendar table in the data view.

2. Click on Mark as date table icon on the Calendars menu located in the Table tools.

3. Select the option Mark as date table.

4. The Mark as date table window will appear.

5. Select Date from the Date Column menu. The message Validated Successfully should appear.

6. Then click Ok.

  

 



Step 2.4 - Add columns to the Calendar table.

1. Select the Calendar table in the data view.

2. Click on New column to add columns.

3. Type in MonthNumber = MONTH(Calendar[Date]) in the formula bar and press enter when done.

4. Repeat the last step to create the following columns:


MonthNumber = MONTH(Calendar[Date])

MonthName = FORMAT(Calendar[Date], "MMMM")

DayName = FORMAT(Calendar[Date], "DDDD")

DayNumber = WEEKDAY(Calendar[Date], 2)

Year = YEAR('Calendar'[Date])

 

For the last column, Decade, make sure to type all of it in the formula bar.

Decade =

VAR DecadeStart =

    ROUNDDOWN ( 'Calendar'[Year], -1 )

VAR DecadeEnd = DecadeStart + 10

RETURN

    DecadeStart & "'s"


 

 




Step 2.5 – Sort Columns by another Column.

1. This step will let you order properly the months and day by name.

2. In the Data view, select the Calendar table and click on the MonthNumber Column.

3. Then click on Sort by column from the Sort menu in the Column tools.

4. Select the column to sort by. In this case, select the MonthNumber.

5. Repeat the steps for DayName. This time sort by DayNumber.
